'''Tom Carver''' (born November 2, 1960) is a writer and former [[BBC]] [[foreign correspondent]]. He is also the step-grandson of [[Bernard Montgomery, 1st Viscount Montgomery of Alamein|Field Marshal Montgomery]].

==Biography==
His grandfather [[Oswald Carver]] was an Olympic oarsman who rowed in the 1908 Summer Olympics in London. He was killed during the battle of Gallipoli in 1916 aged 28. His grandmother, [[Elizabeth Carver]] married [[Bernard Montgomery]] in 1927. Montgomery would go onto to become [[Field Marshal Montgomery]] in [[World War II]].

Carver was 15 when Viscount Montgomery died, and formed part of the guard of honour at his funeral at [[St. George's Chapel, Windsor Castle]] as part of his school cadet force.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://historytodaymagazine.blogspot.com/2009/10/roger-moorhouse-in-conversation-with.html|title= Roger Moorhouse in conversation with Tom Carver|publisher=HistoryToday|accessdate= 9 October 2009|date= 9 October 2009}}</ref>

==Career==
Carver joined the [[BBC]] as a local radio trainee. He became a [[BBC]] foreign [[correspondent]], reporting on the withdrawal of the [[Soviet Army]] from [[Afghanistan]], the collapse of the [[Soviet Union]] and the first [[Gulf War]]. In 1991, he was sent into northern [[Iraq]] to investigate reports that [[Saddam Hussein]] was massacring the [[Kurds]] and became one of the first journalists to witness the exodus of half a million Kurds across the mountains towards [[Turkey]].

In 1991 he became [[BBC]] [[Africa]] correspondent for three years, covering the US-led invasion of [[Somalia]] otherwise known as [[Operation Restore Hope]], the [[Angolan Civil War]] and the transition to black majority rule in [[South Africa]]. In 1994, he covered the [[Rwandan Genocide]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.writingstudio.co.za/page1474.html|title= The art of writing and making films: SHOOTING DOGS|publisher=The Writing Studio|accessdate=1994|year=1994}}</ref>

In 1995 he reported on the [[Massacre of Srebrenica]] during the [[Bosnian War]] as the BBC<U+2019>s Defence Correspondent.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/player/nol/newsid_4670000/newsid_4673500/4673587.stm|title=Film reveals scale of Srebrenica atrocity|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=July 1995|date=July 1995}}</ref>

In 1997, he became the [[BBC]] [[Washington, D.C.|Washington]] correspondent remaining in the post for 8 years.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/special_report/1998/clinton_scandal/155467.stm|title=With bill Clinton in martha<U+2019>s vineyard during monica Lewinsky scandal|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=August 21, 1998 | date=21 August 1998}}</ref> He reported on the serial killings of dozens of women in [[Ciudad Ju<U+00E1>rez|Juarez, Mexico]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/442618.stm|title=Covered the mass murders of women in Juarez, Mexico|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=September 9, 1999 | date=9 September 1999}}</ref> and covered the disputed [[United States presidential election, 2000|2000 presidential election]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://usproxy.bbc.com/2/hi/talking_point/forum/1050115.stm|title=BBC Washington correspondent during 2000 election|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=5 December 2000}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/in_depth/americas/2000/us_elections/election_challenge/996852.stm|title= Internet shaping journalism|accessdate=29 October 2000 | date=29 October 2000 | work=BBC News}}</ref> He was appointed [[BBC Newsnight]] [[Washington, D.C.|Washington]] correspondent<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/programmes/newsnight/3121188.stm|title=BBC Washington correspondent for Newsnight|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=18 September 2003 | date=18 September 2003}}</ref> and was an eyewitness at September 11.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/programmes/from_our_own_correspondent/1544714.stm|title=Eyewitness During September 11th|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=15 September 2001 | date=15 September 2001}}</ref>

In 2003 he was one of the few journalists to travel with Vice President [[Dick Cheney]] through the [[Middle East]] in a prelude to the [[Iraq war]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/middle_east/1884886.stm|title=Traveled with Cheney in run up to Iraq War|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=21 March 2002 | date=21 March 2002}}</ref> He covered the [[2004 election]] and was at the [[Democratic Convention]] when [[Barack Obama]] gave his first national speech.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/3940511.stm|title=At 2004 democratic convention when Obama first emerged|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=31 July 2004 | date=31 July 2004}}</ref> He left the [[BBC]] after the election to become Senior Vice President at Control Risks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lloyds.com/News_Centre/360_risk_insight/The_debate_on_terrorism_and_political_risk/360_live_debate_New_York/Speakers/Tom_Carver.htm|title=SVP at Control Risks}}</ref> 

And then in 2008, he took up the post of Senior Vice President at Chlopak, Leonard, Schechter a Washington-based communications consultancy<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.clsdc.com/tomcarver|title=SVP at CLS}}</ref> before joining the [[Carnegie Endowment for International Peace]] as head of Global Communications.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.carnegieendowment.org/publications/index.cfm?fa=view&id=42335|title= Tom Carver to head global communications for Carnegie Endowment|publisher= Carnegie Endowment for International Peace|accessdate= 19 January 2011|date=19 January 2011}}</ref>

Carver has written for numerous newspapers, including ''[[The Independent]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http:/www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/white-house-sets-attack-dogs-on-kerry-as-disappearing-dean-leaves-field-clear-575231.html|title=Contributor to Independent newspaper|publisher=The Independent|accessdate=1 February 2004}}</ref> ''[[London Review of Books]]'', ''[[The Sunday Times]]'', ''[[New Statesman]]'' and ''[[The Guardian]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2004/jun/04/usa.comment|title=Guardian article on Green Card hell |publisher=Guardian.co.uk|accessdate=4 June 2004 | location=London | date=4 June 2004 | first=Tom | last=Carver}}</ref>

Carver is the author of ''Where the hell have you been?'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tomcarver.net/book_excerpt.html|title=www.tomcarver.net|publisher=Short Books|accessdate=October 2009}}</ref> a bestselling account of his father Richard Carver<U+2019>s adventures during [[World War II]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.amazon.co.uk/dp/1906021538|title=Amazon link for book}}</ref>

===Personal life===
Carver is married to [[BBC]] anchor [[Katty Kay]]. The couple have four children.

